## Alternative Version with More Features

Here's a slightly more robust version with some error handling and the ability to specify a port:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"net/http"
	"os"
	"strconv"
)

func main() {
	// Default port
	port := "8080"

	// Check if a port is specified as a command line argument
	if len(os.Args) > 1 {
		port = os.Args[1]
	}

	// HandleFunc registers the handler function for the path "/"
	http.HandleFunc("/", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
		// Set the content type
		w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "text/plain")

		// Write the response
		fmt.Fprint(w, "Hello, World!")
	})

	// Listen and serve on the specified port
	address := ":" + port
	fmt.Printf("Server is listening on port %s...\n", port)
	err := http.ListenAndServe(address, nil)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Printf("Error starting server: %s\n", err)
		os.Exit(1)
	}
}
```

## Running the Alternative Version

You can specify a different port when starting the server:
```bash
go run main.go 9090
```

Then visit `http://localhost:9090` in your browser.

Both versions will respond with "Hello, World!" to any HTTP request.
